"1100":"1100","about 1189":"omkring 1189","about 1155":"omkring 1155","Mendham, Suffolk, England":"Mendham, Suffolk, England","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","Huntingfield, Suffolk, England":"Huntingfield, Suffolk, England","Herleton Manor, East Bradenham, Norfolk, England":"Bradenham, Norfolk, England","Clumal Priory, Mendenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mendham, Suffolk, England"},"nl":{"about 1117–about 1189":"circa 1117–circa 1189","1117–1189":"1117–1189","1115–1155":"1115–1155","1145–1204":"1145–1204","1100–1155":"1100–1155","1117":"1117","1204":"1204","1115":"1115","1145":"1145","1189":"1189","about 1117":"circa 1117","1155":"1155","1100":"1100","about 1189":"circa 1189","about 1155":"circa 1155","Mendham, Suffolk, England":"Mendham, Suffolk, England","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","Huntingfield, Suffolk, England":"Huntingfield, Suffolk, England","Herleton Manor, East Bradenham, Norfolk, England":"Bradenham, Norfolk, England","Clumal Priory, Mendenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mendham, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"about 1117–about 1189":"about 1117–about 1189","1117–1189":"1117–1189","1115–1155":"1115–1155","1145–1204":"1145–1204","1100–1155":"1100–1155","1117":"1117","1204":"1204","1115":"1115","1145":"1145","1189":"1189","about 1117":"about 1117","1155":"1155","1100":"1100","about 1189":"about 1189","about 1155":"about 1155","Mendham, Suffolk, England":"Mendham, Suffolk, England","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","Huntingfield, Suffolk, England":"Huntingfield, Suffolk, England","Herleton Manor, East Bradenham, Norfolk, England":"Bradenham, Norfolk, England","Clumal Priory, Mendenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mendham, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Kyong, Kyong Suk, Young, Chae, Chi Young, Hang, Kil, Rin, Sang Hun, Chang, Chong, Insoo, Kum, Sun Young, Yom, Young Hwan.  Cambodian Kiwan, Oeurn, Phoeun, Pich, Saroeuth, Seung, Sophath, Sophea, Yoeun, Phan, Son.  Indian Shanti, Harendra.","Indian (Uttar Pradesh): Brahmin name, from Sanskrit <i>om</i>, the Hindu sacred and mystic syllable uttered at the beginning of prayers.","Cambodian: written ឱម, corresponding to the exclamation of solemn affirmation, of Sanskrit origin (see 1 above), chanted by Buddhist monks."],"variants":[{"name":"Oum","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heang, Hye, Kam, Kan, Kheng, Khin, Kun, Sang, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"Sibilla","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Emilio, Angelo, Antonio, Rocco, Sal, Salvatore, Silvio.  Spanish Jose, Juan, Zoraida.","Italian (mainly southern): from the medieval female personal name <i>Sibilia</i>, from Old French <i>Sibilie</i> (see   Sibley  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Scibelli","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Gennaro, Filomena, Marco, Paolo, Salvator.","Italian (Campania): patronymic or plural form of a variant of the female personal name   Sibilia   (compare   Scibilia  )."]},{"name":"Scibilia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Giuseppe, Rosario, Angelo, Antonio, Carmela, Fabio, Fortunato, Gaspare, Girolamo, Rocco, Sal, Salvatore, Santo.","Italian (Sicily): from a variant of the female personal name   Sibilia  ."]},{"name":"Sibley","meanings":["English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Sibily</i>, Old French <i>Sibilie</i>, from Latin <i>Sibilia</i>, from Greek <i>Sibylla</i>, a title of obscure origin borne by various oracular priestesses in classical times. In Christian mythology the sibyls came to be classed as pagan prophets (who had prophesied the coming of Christ), and hence the name was an acceptable one that could be bestowed on a Christian child."]}]},{"name":"Sybil","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Sybilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sibilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sybille","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Sybil</b> ."]},{"name":"Sibella","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Sybil of Sibilla de Gigney was born about 1117, in Bradenham, Norfolk, England as the daughter of Roger de Gigney. She had at least 1 son with William de Huntingfield. She died about 1189, in Huntingfield, Suffolk, England, at the age of 74, and was buried in Mendham, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"about 1117–about 1189":"umbes 1117–umbes 1189","1117–1189":"1117–1189","1115–1155":"1115–1155","1145–1204":"1145–1204","1100–1155":"1100–1155","1117":"1117","1204":"1204","1115":"1115","1145":"1145","1189":"1189","about 1117":"umbes 1117","1155":"1155","1100":"1100","about 1189":"umbes 1189","about 1155":"umbes 1155","Mendham, Suffolk, England":"Mendham, Suffolk, England","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","Huntingfield, Suffolk, England":"Huntingfield, Suffolk, England","Herleton Manor, East Bradenham, Norfolk, England":"Bradenham, Norfolk, England","Clumal Priory, Mendenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mendham, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1117–about 1189":"noin 1117–noin 1189","1117–1189":"1117–1189","1115–1155":"1115–1155","1145–1204":"1145–1204","1100–1155":"1100–1155","1117":"1117","1204":"1204","1115":"1115","1145":"1145","1189":"1189","about 1117":"noin 1117","1155":"1155","1100":"1100","about 1189":"noin 1189","about 1155":"noin 1155","Mendham, Suffolk, England":"Mendham, Suffolk, England","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","Huntingfi